### TITLE ###
RequiredListRejectsEmptyFirstEntry
### DESCRIPTION ###
A required list blocks an immediate empty line ("at least one value required");
after one value, an empty line finishes.
### INPUT ###
args:
    tags str[]
print(tags)
### ARGS ###
-i
### KEYS ###
enter
"a"
enter
enter
### STDOUT ###
[ "a" ]

### STDERR ###
Equivalent: rad TestCase --color=never --tags a

### FRAMES ###
--- frame 0 (initial) ---
--tags (one per line, empty line to finish)
> █
--- frame 1 (enter) ---
--tags (one per line, empty line to finish)
> █
at least one value required
--- frame 2 (a) ---
--tags (one per line, empty line to finish)
> a█
--- frame 3 (enter) ---
--tags a
--- frame 4 (initial) ---
--tags (one per line, empty line to finish)
> █
### TITLE ###
ExcludesSkipsPrompt
### DESCRIPTION ###
A CLI-supplied arg that mutually excludes another suppresses the latter's
prompt entirely, with a stderr note.
### INPUT ###
args:
    file str? # File input.
    url str? # URL input.

    file mutually excludes url
print("file={file} url={url}")
### ARGS ###
-i
--file
in.txt
### STDOUT ###
file=in.txt url=null

### STDERR ###
Skipping --url (excluded by --file)
Equivalent: rad TestCase --file in.txt --color=never

### TITLE ###
RequiresForcesPrompt
### DESCRIPTION ###
A CLI-supplied arg that mutually requires another forces the latter's prompt:
it loses its skip affordance (empty Enter is blocked, naming the arg that
forced it). The forced arg is nullable - one with a default would satisfy the
requires constraint by itself (see RequiresSatisfiedByDefault).
### INPUT ###
args:
    username str = "" # Username.
    password str? # Password.

    username mutually requires password
print("user={username} pass={password}")
### ARGS ###
-i
--username
alice
### KEYS ###
enter
"pw"
enter
### STDOUT ###
user=alice pass=pw

### STDERR ###
Equivalent: rad TestCase --username alice --color=never --password pw

### FRAMES ###
--- frame 0 (initial) ---
--password: Password.
> █
--- frame 1 (enter) ---
--password: Password.
> █
required by --username
--- frame 2 (p) ---
--password: Password.
> p█
--- frame 3 (w) ---
--password: Password.
> pw█
--- frame 4 (enter) ---
--password pw
### TITLE ###
RequiresSatisfiedByDefault
### DESCRIPTION ###
A requires constraint pointing at a defaulted arg stays satisfied by that
default (ra's has-value semantics), so the prompt keeps its skip affordance.
### INPUT ###
args:
    username str = "" # Username.
    token str = "anon" # Token.

    username mutually requires token
print("user={username} token={token}")
### ARGS ###
-i
--username
alice
### KEYS ###
enter
### STDOUT ###
user=alice token=anon

### STDERR ###
Equivalent: rad TestCase --username alice --color=never

### FRAMES ###
--- frame 0 (initial) ---
--token: Token.
> █Default: anon
--- frame 1 (enter) ---
--token (skip - default: anon)
### TITLE ###
FloatRangeRevalidation
### DESCRIPTION ###
Float args validate inline like ints: out-of-range blocks Enter, editing
clears the error, and a valid value submits.
### INPUT ###
args:
    ratio float # Mix ratio.
    ratio range [0, 1]
print("ratio={ratio}")
### ARGS ###
-i
### KEYS ###
"5"
enter
backspace
"0.5"
enter
### STDOUT ###
ratio=0.5

### STDERR ###
Equivalent: rad TestCase --color=never --ratio 0.5

### FRAMES ###
--- frame 0 (initial) ---
--ratio: Mix ratio.
> █
--- frame 1 (5) ---
--ratio: Mix ratio.
> 5█
--- frame 2 (enter) ---
--ratio: Mix ratio.
> 5█
must be in range [0, 1]
--- frame 3 (backspace) ---
--ratio: Mix ratio.
> █
--- frame 4 (0) ---
--ratio: Mix ratio.
> 0█
--- frame 5 (.) ---
--ratio: Mix ratio.
> 0.█
--- frame 6 (5) ---
--ratio: Mix ratio.
> 0.5█
--- frame 7 (enter) ---
--ratio 0.5
### TITLE ###
NegativeNumbersInIntList
### DESCRIPTION ###
Negative numbers entered for a number list ride the =-form (--nums=-5) in the
synthesized argv, so the final parse cannot mistake them for flags.
### INPUT ###
args:
    nums int[]
print(nums)
### ARGS ###
-i
### KEYS ###
"-5"
enter
"3"
enter
enter
### STDOUT ###
[ -5, 3 ]

### STDERR ###
Equivalent: rad TestCase --color=never --nums=-5 --nums 3

### FRAMES ###
